			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">December 17, 2014 2:46 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//douthat.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/12/17/on-the-liberal-marriage-hypothesis/" data-title="On The Liberal Marriage Hypothesis" data-description="Why progressive ideas don&#039;t necessarily hold the key to marriage&#039;s future flourishing.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/14/opinion/sunday/ross-douthat-the-imitation-of-marriage.html?rref=collection%2Fcolumn%2Fross-douthat">Sunday column</a> was written in dialogue with an increasingly popular idea among many progressive writers on marriage and family: The theory that the falling divorce rate (among other indicators) among college-educated Americans is evidence that marriage has been successfully reinvented in the wake of the sexual revolution; that progressive ideas â the acceptance of premarital sex and cohabitation, an egalitarian vision of gender roles in parenting and breadwinning, a stronger emphasis on romantic compatibility and personal fulfillmentÂ âÂ have basically been responsible forÂ that reinvention; and that Â theÂ main cultural force (setting aside economics)Â preventing working class Americans from embracing this successful reinvention is the unfortunate persistence of traditionalist norms and attitudes about sex and gender roles.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One of the writers to make this argument recently, Bloomberg View&#8217;s Noah Smith, <a href="//noahpinionblog.blogspot.com/2014/12/ross-douthat-ponders-liberal-marriage.html">read my weekend column</a> as a partial concession to this view â a baby step, if you will, toward the fulness of progressive truth. Naturally I prefer to think of the column as an attempt to sift the wisdom from the folly in his perspective. And to make that sifting a little more explicit, let me use <a href="//noahpinionblog.blogspot.com/2014/07/are-liberals-rescuing-marriage.html">Smith&#8217;s original distillation</a> of the liberalism-is-saving-marriage argument, which I&#8217;ll quote here:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What if sexual permissiveness and feminism, instead of being toxic to the institution of marriage, are the key to saving it?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That might sound crazy, but hereâs the case in a nutshell. If you wait until marriage to have sex, youâre taking an enormous risk. What if youâre not compatible? Or what if you regret not having shopped around?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Sexual permissiveness means that sex isnât about marriage. But that means that <em>marriage isnât about sex</em>. Most of the upper-class liberal educated Americans I know who are in stable, happy marriages had their share of premarital sex. Knowing what that lifestyle is like &#8212; and realizing that they wanted more &#8212; allowed them to be more content in their marriages, and more realistic about what marriage is all about (i.e., lifetime companionship and raising kids).</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Feminism may be even more important for families. With traditional gender roles, only a man who can be a sole breadwinner is a worthwhile mate. That rules out a lot of men, and it might be a reason why less-educated Americansâ conservative values are holding them back from getting married. Feminism, on the other hand, rewards fathers for sharing child care and housework, and frees them from the heavy burden of antiquated expectations.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In other words, maybe liberal morality is simply better adapted for creating stable two-parent families in a post-industrialized world. Maybe conservative family values are hard but brittle, like diamond, while liberal family values are strong like titanium &#8212; able to bend without breaking.</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So here we have two different ideas. The first is that <em>sexual permissiveness</em> makes for happier, more stable marriages, because people aren&#8217;t just marrying to have sex, because they don&#8217;t have to risk discovering their sexual incompatibility too late, and because they can have their fun and then settle down rather than having a midlife crisis and splitting up later on. The second is that <em>greater equality between the sexes</em>Â makes for happier or more stable marriages, because it frees men and women from imprisoning stereotypes while also making their partnerships better adapted to the demands of a post-industrialized economy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One of these ideas â spoiler: the second one â seems to have much more evidence in its favor than the other. <span id="more-20599"></span>It is, of course, always difficult to figure out exactly howÂ various sexual and romantic choices influence marital happiness and longevity,Â selection effects being what they are. But if Smith&#8217;s hypothesis about sexual permissiveness were correct, one would expect there to be some clear &#8220;permissiveness premium,&#8221; some evidence of a &#8220;shopping-around&#8221; sweet spot that makes the subsequently married more content.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But is there? Well, what does exist is evidence that getting married before the age of twenty is a terrible idea, that delaying marriage boosts female incomes, and that marriages made in one&#8217;s thirties are somewhat more stable (though <a href="//www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0049089X10001183">not as happy</a>, on average) than marriages contracted in one&#8217;sÂ twenties. These points form the most compelling basis possible for the idea that some level of promiscuity must be a good thing for marriages, because it lets people (<a href="//www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2012/09/boys-on-the-side/309062/">especially women</a>, in some arguments) have their fun or get relationship practice while they delay marriage and get their degreesÂ and asset-build and prepare themselves to enter stable bourgeois life in their thirties.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But when you look specifically at sex itself, at patterns of actual sexual activity and their link to marital happiness and longevity, direct evidence for a permissiveness premium is extremely hard to find. And for women, almost all the the data points sharply in the opposite direction. Notwithstanding the potential for regrets, women who only had sex with theirÂ future spouseÂ are <a href="//www.washingtonpost.com/news/rampage/wp/2014/08/26/in-marriages-what-happens-in-vegas-may-not-stay-in-vegas/">more likely to be in a high quality marriage</a> than women who hadÂ a higher number of sexual partners.Â Divorce rates are <a href="//onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1741-3737.2003.00444.x/abstract;jsessionid=2CAC28A08F64E8A7CA6E4DBDFEE30124.f04t03?deniedAccessCustomisedMessage=&amp;userIsAuthenticated=false">higher for women with multiple premarital partners</a> than women who had only one; they&#8217;re <a href="//alt.coxnewsweb.com/shared-blogs/austin/health/upload/2008/11/habitual_livein_lovers_often_n/JOMF%20Lichter%20Article.pdf">twice as high</a> for women who have cohabitated serially than women who only cohabitated with their future husband. Independent of marriage, relationship stability is <a href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23121225">stronger when sex is initiated later</a>, and monogamy and a restricted number of sex partners is <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2011/03/07/opinion/07douthat.html?_r=0">strongly associated with female happiness</a> and emotional well-being, period. AndÂ these results holdÂ irrespective of education levels, as <a href="//family-studies.org/sex-and-divorce-whats-the-connection/">this piece by Brad Wilcox and Nicholas Wolfinger</a> points out: There&#8217;s a stronger correlation between multiple premarital partners and marital instability among less-educated Americans, but well-educated Americans, too, show much stronger marital outcomes when they have fewer premarital partners. (And interestingly, the usual connection between education and stability disappears entirely for people who married their first partner: They&#8217;re equally unlikely to divorce no matter whether they attended college or not.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Now again, given selection effects and other variables there are variousÂ ways to read these findings, and <a href="//douthat.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/12/17/sex-sociology-and-the-single-girl/">all kinds of interesting debates to have</a> about what the female-specific element mightÂ tell us about what kind ofÂ sexual culture we should want. But it&#8217;sÂ very hard to read them as evidence that permissiveness qua permissiveness is a big driver of marital stability or satisfaction, or that people who reserve sex, not necessarily for marriage, but for relationships that seemÂ plausiblyÂ premarital are taking the kind of big risk that Smith suggests they are. And they seem at leastÂ compatible with the idea, frequently raised by conservatives (<a href="//douthat.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/01/29/social-liberalism-as-class-warfare/">myself included</a>) and scoffed at a bit by Smith, that an sexually-permissive culture benefits an upper class that&#8217;s still taught forms of restraint and caution <em>implicitly</em> at every level of its education, and that therefore ends up being less promiscuous overall and less likely to serially cohabit before marriage than the rest of the societyÂ &#8230; and ends up happier and more settled in marriage as a consequence.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Now let&#8217;s talk about the second half of the liberal marriage hypothesis, the idea that gender egalitarianism is good for modern unions, or alternatively that modern couples need to adapt to a more egalitarian landscape â less strictly-gendered specialization, more labor-sharing inside the home, a greater acceptance of women working outside itÂ Â âÂ if they want their marriages to succeed. There I think Smith&#8217;s argument is much stronger, with <a href="//www.deseretnews.com/article/865576340/BYU-USU-study-says-marriage-thrives-on-shared-chores-strong-dad-child-bond.html?pg=all">various forms of research</a> to buttress it, and a version of it applies not only to marital stability but to family formation, period: If you look at various societies, from Japan to southern Europe, where the economy has changed while the culture remains strikingly patriarchal in many ways, you don&#8217;t alwaysÂ see high divorce rates but you <em>do</em> see plunging birth and marriage rates, which suggests thatÂ hanging on to certain patriarchal models can take a toll on the very creationÂ of families, not only their happiness and resilience.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the American context, whereÂ women are outpacing men in education and traditionally male sectors of the economy are weak,Â the old ideaÂ â which is, yes, still more prevalent among the less educatedÂ â that fathers and husbands should be sole providers and that women shouldn&#8217;t work at all outside the home clearly creates a potential obstacle to forging stable marriages, because it no longer matches up with either female expectations or economic realities. And so the gradual evolution of American opinion (which you can see charted in an interesting context <a href="//www.cmc.edu/govt/FacMember/Shields/Shields_Politics_Motherhood.pdf">in this paper on the pro-life movement</a>) toward what was once an exclusively progressive premise aboutÂ women&#8217;s roles in the home and workforce does, indeed, seem like a good thing, and a case where certain liberal and/or feministÂ ideas (now shared more broadly) about marriage are necessary to its present and near-futureÂ flourishing.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But as I tried to point out in my column, this argument needs to be qualified, because what Smith and others are casting as a successful &#8220;liberal&#8221; marriage model still often has much stronger traditional elements woven in than that rhetoric would suggest. The division of labor in America&#8217;s more-successful upper-middle-class marriages, in particular, is more egalitarian than &#8220;Father Knows Best&#8221; but still often quite gendered (as <a href="//family-studies.org/its-not-just-the-economy-stupid-why-is-the-working-class-family-really-coming-apart/">this Wilcox post</a> points out), with college-educated husbands bringing home larger shares of household income and wives often preferring part-time work. And that gendered division actually increases at the highest (and, in my experience, most politically liberal) levels of the meritocracy: Wives and mothers who are <em>elite</em> college graduates are <a href="//www.bostonglobe.com/business/2013/05/26/women-graduates-elite-colleges-more-likely-opt-out-workforce/wQAmXRV9WMWtFKph26ORBM/story.html">more likely to opt out of the workforce</a> than the college-educated norm.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Then similarly, college-educated Americas are more religious overall than the secularism of the Pacific Coast and the BosWash corridor would lead one to expect, and more likely to <em>practice</em> a religion than downscale Americans â and since religion is still <a href="//nineteensixty-four.blogspot.com/2013/09/divorce-still-less-likely-among.html">a big factor in marital stability</a>, with <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/03/30/opinion/sunday/douthat-the-christian-penumbra.html">religious practice in particular</a> correlating strongly with low divorce rates, this too seems like a case where &#8220;traditional&#8221; ideas or approaches are still providing crucial support to marriage&#8217;s contemporary resilience among the better-educated strata of society.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And then finally, if you try to pin down <a href="//www.theamericanconservative.com/broke-and-alone-coming-up-short/">their attitudes and values</a>, it isn&#8217;t obvious that working class America&#8217;s struggling menÂ are all stuck in some antiquated patriarchal rut. At times, they seem almost too well adapted to the emotivist, individualist, therapeutic ideas that we tend to think of as more &#8220;progressive&#8221; or modern or what-have-you, when perhaps <a href="//douthat.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/03/the-left-and-masculinity/">certain lost or fading elements of &#8220;traditional masculinity&#8221;</a> might actually still stand them in good stead.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">All of which is to say that if we&#8217;re groping toward ideas or modelsÂ of what marriage should look like in the 21st century, and what kind of choices and cultivated virtues lead to happiness and durability unions and families, describing the future of marriage as necessarily (and happily) &#8220;progressive&#8221; is a kind of quarter-truth. It captures one very important element in contemporary social life, a shift toward more flexible gender roles amid greater female opportunities, that a flourishing marriage culture needs to adapt to, take advantage of, incorporate, accept. But it overstates how dramatically these adaptations, even or especially in their more successful forms, have overwritten more traditional patterns of marital success. And itÂ underrates, as all of contemporary liberalism tends to do, the costsÂ to men and women, parents and children, of a sexual culture that claims to have successfully severed premarital sexual choicesÂ from the marital and familialÂ goods to which they were once assumed to be intimately linked. On the evidence, our culture has done no such thing: The link seems to endure, however obscured, and the idea that weakening orÂ severing it actually makesÂ marriages stronger is a convenient fiction with littleÂ empirical support.</p>
	</div>
